<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ881013-0060 </DOCNO><HL> Business Brief -- American Telephone andamp; Telegraph: Agreement Signed to Build Caribbean Fiber-Optic Cable </HL><SO> </SO><CO> T LATAM MCIC GTE UT WU </CO><IN> TEL </IN><TEXT>   American Telephone andamp; Telegraph Co. said it signed an agreement with 11 other companies to build an undersea fiber-optic cable in the Caribbean for $130 million.    The 2,430-mile cable will link the U.S. with Puerto Rico, the Dominican Republic, Jamaica and Colombia. It is scheduled to be completed in 1990 and will be 48% owned by ATandamp;T.    Other owners include MCI Communications Co., US Sprint Communications Co., Western Union Corp., and phone concerns in several Caribbean islands, an ATandamp;T spokesman said. US Sprint is jointly owned by United Telecommunications Inc. and GTE Corp.    As is typical with international undersea cables, ATandamp;T will construct and lay the cable. It will be used by the various owners to transmit phone and data calls.    In a related matter, the ATandamp;T spokesman said ATandamp;T is negotiating to build two new cable ships. ATandamp;T currently owns two ships that lay and repair cables. </TEXT></DOC>